  "body": "It would be great to have these sync-free methods. Whenever we write to e.g. currentblock, we could set \r\natomic integers to expose these methods for callers. These are used in the p2p-communication aswell as in rpc-calls, e.g. \r\nestimate gas. \r\n\r\nI implemented one of them a while ago in https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/15104 , but I think it has bitrotted away by now. \r\n\r\n```golang\r\n\r\n\t// returns current total difficulty, the same that would be returned by \r\n\t// pm.blockchain.CurrentBlock()\r\n\t// pm.blockchain.GetTd(currentBlock.Hash(), currentBlock.NumberU64())\r\n\t// i.e , the currentBlock.\r\n \r\n\ttd := pm.blockchain.CurrentTd()\r\n\r\n\t// Returns the number of the pm.blockchain.CurrentBlock()\r\n\tnumber := pm.blockchain.CurrentNumber()\r\n\r\n\t// Returns the number of pm.blockchain.CurrentFastBlock()\r\n\tfastNumber := pm.blockchain.CurrentFastNumber()\r\n\r\n\r\n\t// Returns the GasLimit() for CurrentBlock()\r\n\tgasLimit := pm.blockchain.CurrentGasLimit()\r\n```\r\nI believe this is the cause for https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/issues/15739 , aswell as peers being dropped/unresponsive during high load -- particularly when the drive IO is the bottleneck, since the blockchain mutex will be held almost constantly. \r\n  ",
